		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 7:35 PM 2000 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=11&mid=9665470391340&num=9&post=1&replyto=96664175629131"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=96664175629131></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=480"><span id=>Torshen</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>2 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>*Whispers*&nbsp;&nbsp;Here is my secret.  I am Torshen, an erudite wizard, and found an excellent solo ledge in blackburrow that easily took me from twelth to sixteenth level. It also can provide experience far past these levels, but loses some of its charm after sixteenth. (this may not apply to you just yet, but if you find yourself in blackburrow, watch for the ledge I am talking about.  Then you can begin to judge when you are ready to solo there.)  Just as you enter blackburrow there is a tree to your left.  It is a well known fact that this tree is a pit trap, dropping you into a pool deep in blackburrow. If you are lower level the three patrolling gnolls around the pool will have your hide, but around tenth to eleventh (?) they will begin to ignore you.  Looking around you will see a bridge and small waterfall.  Head toward the waterfall, staying on the ledge to your left.  As you move along the ledge look to your right.  Standing above you, across the stream, will be an elite gnoll guard, gnoll shaman, or gnoll commander.  Probably conning white, yellow or red.  At this point you need to know how the other monsters in blackburrow will react to you.  If gnolls still attack you, this fight is not for you, but if regular gnolls leave you alone you are ready to attempt this kill.  Use Root on the gnoll, then begin using your DD spells to take him down.  BOLT SPELLS WILL NOT WORK! They will almost always hit the wall ledge instead of the gnoll.  The secret to this strategy is knowing how the creature will react.  Apparently, this gnoll is scared of water and will not simply jump the gap to kill you.  He will run in a huge loop just to get you.  DD spells will still be able to hit him, giving you three to four free shots before he closes with you.  By now he is so weak that only a little more damage is needed to make him run (if he hasn't already!) then another spell or two to drop him.  Remember you will be fighting a yellow or red con, so the exp will be excellent, and the loot is good too.  Sound too good to be true?  It might be, if you aren't careful.  There is a gnoll watcher waiting beyond the door, where you cannot see him.  When the gnoll you are fighting moves, he will run close enough to the door to alert the watcher, who will also come for you.  He too has a long way to run, so you are okay if you are fast.  So long as your target stays rooted you have nothing to worry about, but once he runs the clock is ticking.  My response to this was to bind myself just outside blackburrow.  After my main target was killed a quick gate would bring me to safety where i could med and recover.  The other benefit to being bound just outside blackburrow is that, if you do die, you can quickly mem your most powerful attack spell, and charge back into the fight. As I gained levels I found I could take the main target and the watcher.  It may take a few attempts to get your timing down, and learn to budget your mana.  For this to work you probably want to have two dd spells memorized, your most powerful and a lesser low mana version.  You will also want to memorize gate, root, and don't forget those all important shield spells! There is one more hazard I will mention while I am thinking about it.  Straight across from the gnoll, where you will be standing is a corner in the wall, with a small upward slope.  There is a hole in the world in that spot, and your corpse will fall through if you die there.  Then you must summon a GM to rescue it.  Just remember to take a step away from the wall while fighting and you will be fine.  <br><br>The important thing to remember, and this always applies, is that you are a wizard, intelligence and strategy are your best tools.  Learn your enemies, watch how they react to you, where they run, and who they bring.  Learning a monsters response to you is more powerful than any spell you can ever learn!</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
